<div class="entry-content primary-content-column columns small-12 medium-8">
<aside class="series-card row">
<div class="series-image small-4 columns">
<a href='https://truthout.org/series/fighting-for-our-lives-the-movement-for-medicare-for-all/'>
<img width="200" height="113" src="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/2018_0129med-200x113.jpg" class="attachment-hd_thumbnail size-hd_thumbnail" alt="Fighting for Our Lives - The Movement for Medicare for All" srcset="https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/2018_0129med-200x113.jpg 200w, https://truthout.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/2018_0129med-400x225.jpg 400w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" />
</a>
</div>
<div class="series-info small-8 columns">
<p class='meta-label'>Part of the Series</p>
<h5 class='series-title'><a href='https://truthout.org/series/fighting-for-our-lives-the-movement-for-medicare-for-all/'>Fighting for Our Lives: The Movement for Medicare for All</a></h5>
</div>
</aside>
<p>A couple of weeks ago, as countries scrambled to protect their citizens from the COVID-19 pandemic by closing borders and quarantining travelers, the Norwegian University of Science and Technology, upon the &ldquo;recommendation of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs,&rdquo; took the unprecedented step of <a href="https://www.marketwatch.com/story/norwegian-university-urges-students-to-return-home-from-the-us-cites-poorly-developed-health-services-2020-03-15">urging all students who are studying abroad to return home</a>. In the announcement, they emphasized the need to return home if students are living in a country with &ldquo;poorly developed health services and infrastructure &hellip; for example the USA.&rdquo; The word spread quickly on social media that the United States had been singled out as an example of a country with poor health care infrastructure, with many people in the U.S. agreeing that we lack the capacity to handle the pandemic.</p>
<p>There are many reasons why the United States, which spends the most per capita on health care each year of any wealthy nation, is lagging behind other countries in health care access. Compared to other wealthy nations, the United States stands out for lacking a universal health care system and for prioritizing corporate profits over health. This has led to a fragmented health care system that is ill-equipped for a coordinated response in a time of crisis, such as the current pandemic.</p>
<p>If there is any question that profits matter more than health in the United States, here are three recent examples.</p><div class="truth-post-content-high  inline-callout-container" id="truth-255792"><aside class=" callout inline-callout callout--subscribe callout--dark" id="truth-255397">
<h2>The stories you care about, right at your fingertips</h2>
<p>Get <em>Truthout&rsquo;</em>s daily edition delivered to your inbox.</p>
